<div class='allCommunityAnswers'>
<div class='communityAnswer'>
<div class='communityAnswerBody'>
<div class='answererUserIcon'>
<a class="leftAlignedImage userPhoto" href="/user/show/119786547-claudio"><img alt="" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/m_100x100-c7bfe730633c9983e27caaa66a8e244a.png" /></a>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerTextContainer'>
<span class='communityAnswererName'>
<a href="/user/show/119786547-claudio">Claudio</a>
</span>
<span class='communityAnswerText'>
<span class="expandableContainer"><span class="truncatedContent">I&apos;ve started the book twice and was pretty launched in it, but twice I gave up. Somehow, in the middle, it kind of loses you, don&apos;t it? I think it&apos;s t<a class="jsShow showAction" href="#">…more</a></span><span class="fullContent">I've started the book twice and was pretty launched in it, but twice I gave up. Somehow, in the middle, it kind of loses you, don't it? I think it's the barocque language and some inaction back in the clown/circus phase. It's a great story, though.<br />I'll give it another try soon.<br /><br /> <a class="jsHide hideAction" href="#">(less)</a></span></span>
</span>
</div>
</div>
